  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
            <p xml:id="NA386-kiḷavi">itu parattaiyiṉ maṟuttanta talaimakaṟku vāyiṉ nērnta tōḻi talaimakaḷai “mukampukuval” eṉa muṟpaṭṭā ṭalaimakaṇmāṭṭu niṉṟa poṟāmai nīṅkāmaiyaṟintu piṟitoṉṟaṉ mēlvaittup “pāviyē ṉiṉṟu pētaimai ceytēṉ. em perumāṭṭi kuṟippuṇarntu vaḻippaṭuvē ṉāvēṉmaṉṉō” veṉac colliyatu.</p>
            <p xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante, who had granted [her] mediation to HIM who had been brought back from the other woman, said: “Today sinful me has committed a folly. Surely I will be on [my] way after having understood the intention of our lady?”, putting it one another thing while knowing that the jealousy was not abating which remained in HER, [being one] who had approached HER before with [the words] “I seek [your] favour”.</p>
            </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA386">
<l>            ciṟukaṭ paṉṟip peruñciṉa vorutta</l>
<l>            ṟuṟukaṭ kaṇṇi kāṉava ruḻuta</l>
<l>            kulavukkura lēṉaṉ mānti ñāṅkar</l>
<l>            viṭaraḷaip paḷḷi vēṅkai yañcātu</l>
<l>            kaḻaivaḷar cāraṟ ṟuñcu nāṭa</l>
<l>            ṉaṇaṅkuṭai yaruñcū ṭarukuva ṉeṉanī</l>
<l>            nummō raṉṉōr tuṉṉā rivaiyeṉat</l>
<l>            terintatu viyanteṉ ṟōḻi paṇintunaṅ</l>
<l>            kalkeḻu ciṟukuṭip poliya</l>
<l>            vatuvai yeṉṟavar vanta ñāṉṟē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>          The man from a land, where the wrathful male</l>
<l rend="indent">          of the small-eyed pig is sleeping on the bamboo-grown slope,</l>
<l rend="indent">          without fear, by the Vēṅkai tree<note place="foot">Here tradition understands the <term xml:lang="ta">viṭar aḷai paḷḷi vēṅkai</term> as a kenning for the tiger, probably because it is unclear why the pig should fear a <term xml:lang="ta">Vēṅkai</term> tree, but it seems as well possible to see the tree as a further locative and the fear as fear of retaliation for the stolen millet.</note> in [its] resting place within a cave,</l>
<l rend="indent2">          later, after having fed on the millet with gleaming ears</l>
<l rend="indent2">          ploughed for by the forest people with chaplets with thick nectar,</l>
<l>        I wondered at what I had understood, friend, saying [to him]:</l>
<l rend="indent">          “O you, saying ‘I give a rare oath dedicated to the fearful deity’<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṇaṅku uṭai arum cūḷ</term>: here <term xml:lang="ta">aṇaṅku</term> is supposed by T.V.G. to mean the fearful deity on whom the oath is made. There are indeed parallels (cf. KT 53), and the semantic development of <term xml:lang="ta">aṇaṅku</term> (see Rajam 1986) makes this seem possible, too.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">          your people are such as not to adhere to these [words].”</l>
<l rend="indent2">          – at the time he came [to propose] marriage, humbly,</l>
<l rend="indent2">          so that our stony little hamlet would flourish.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
    </text>
